   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "bfd2b728-6aa8-4ffd-bf4f-1ba96dce5584",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(a) Since X is uniformly distributed, every interval of equal width will have equal no of data points on average. So in we will using around 10% of the data points on average to make predictions in this case."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d12e794b-23e9-402f-8b0f-4dd6906b5a42",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(b) Since X1, X2 are both uniformly distributed. On average 10% of data points will have X1 in the range [0.55, 0.65]. Out of these 10%, 10% on average will have have X2 in the range [0.3, 0.4]. So, fraction of points we are considering now to make predictions are 0.1*0.1 = 0.01.\n",
    "So, we are no only considering 1 % data points on average for making the predictions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "28d58341-cdc3-4a29-9645-7e82583c8580",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(c) Similar to case (b), this time we will be only considering = 0.1*0.1*...p times = 0.1^p\n",
    "so, in this case we will be considering 0.1^100 or 10^-100 or 10^-98 % of the points.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "87401ada-0204-4a78-9b24-9155bd8819cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(d) we can clearly see from above parts that the no. of datapoint near a given obsersation get's so astronomically small as we increase no. of predictors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "baed690c-eb81-46b2-a6bd-bde2a6be9dc1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "(e) For p=1, we are basically considering a line segment. So for uniform distribution, it should just have length of 0.1.\n",
    "    For p=2, we are considering a square, so let's side of the square be s, s^2 = 0.1 => s = sqrt(0.1) = 0.316\n",
    "    For p = 100, s^100 = 0.1 => s = (0.1)^(1/100) = 0.977\n",
    "\n",
    "    As, we can see with 100 sides we are almost covering all the available space."
   ]
  }
 ],
